              <h2 id="infer">1. Inferential Statistics</h2>
              <p>Most of the time, statistician can only get sample out of the big population because acquire the whole population is expensive, take very
                long time and inefficient. While using descriptive statistics can help summarize the characteristics of dataset, 
                inferential statistics can help us make a decision and prediction about the larger population. 
              </p>
              <p>For example: Inferential Statistics:
                A statistician randomly select a sample of Computer Science in WA state, collect data on their final exam score and other features. 
                In this case, we can used inferential statistic to make estimates and test hypothesis about the population of computer science in WA based on the sample.  
              </p>
              <h3>1.1 Sampling error</h3>
              <p>
                Since the sample size is smaller than population, this might create a sample error. Sampling error which is the difference between population values 
                called (parameter) and called sample values called (statistics). 
                <ul class="box">
                  <li>A <b>statistic</b> is a measure that describes the sample (sample mean, sample standard deviation)</li>
                  <li>A <b>population</b> is a measure that describe the whole population (population mean, population standard deviation)</li>
                </ul>
                Since in most cases, we do not know the real population parameter, we can used inferential statistics to estimate these parameter that will take the 
                sampling error into account. There are two types of estimations that can be used to estimate about the population: point estimate and interval estimate. <br><br>
                <ul class="box">
                  <li>A <b>point estimate</b> is a single value estimate of parameter. For example, a sample mean is a point estimate of population mean</li>
                  <li>An <b>interval estimate</b> provides a range of value that a value of parameter expected to lie. A confidence interval is an example of interval estimate</li>
                </ul>
              </p>
