              <h2>2. Confidence Interval</h2>
              <p class="inter"><b>Confidence interval</b> is used to estimate the range that a parameter could lie. It is useful estimate as it into account the 
                sample error. <br>
                While a point estimate give a precise value for each parameter, a confidence interval tells the uncertainty of the point estimate. 
                They are both useful for using together. <br>
                Each confidence interval associated with confidence level. A confidence level have the probability (or percentage) that containing the parameter 
                estimate if you repeat the study again. <br>
                Therefore, 95% confidence interval tells us that we keep repeat our study exactly the same way with a new sample 100 times,
                you can expect your estimate to lie within the specified range of values 95 of the times.Although, we can say that 95% of the time, our estimate will 
                lie between the range, you cannot say for sure that the actul parameter will. 
                That’s because you can’t know the true value of the population parameter without collecting data from the full population.<br>
                However, with random sampling and a suitable sample size, you can reasonably expect your confidence interval to contain the parameter a certain percentage of the time.
              </p>
              <p class="inter">
                 For example, you want to know the average salary of computer science graduate students from UWA. After collecting survey responses from a ramdom sample, you calculate point estimate 
                 and confidence interval. The sample salary of graduate student student is $56,000. 
                 With random sampling, a 95% confidence interval of [$50,000 $12,000] means you can be reasonably confident that the average salary of UWA computer science graduate was between 
                 $50,000 to $120,000
              </p>
