              <h3>3.1 Hypothesis testing step</h3>
              <p>In order to perform hypothesis testing, there are five main steps:</p>
              <ol class="box">
                <li>1. State the research hypothesis as null hypothesis H<sub>o</sub> and alternative Hypothesis H<sub>1</sub></li>
                <li>2. Collect the data in a way to test the hypothesis</li>
                <li>3. Perform an appropriate statistical test</li>
                <li>4. Decide whether the null hypothesis is supported or refused according to p-value or crtical-test </li>
                <li>5. Make a conclusion on the finding</li>
              </ol>
              <p class="inter"> For example: You want to test whether there is a relationship between gender and height<br>
                <b>Step 1:</b> <br>
                H<sub>0</sub>: male are not taller than women <br>
                H<sub>1</sub>: male are not taller than women <br>
                <b>Step 2:</b> <br>
                To test differences in average height between men and women, your sample should have an equal proportion of men and women, 
                and cover a variety of socio-economic classes and any other variables that might influence average height. <br>
                <b>Step 3:</b> <br>
                Based on the type of data you collected, you perform a one-tailed t-test to test whether men are in fact taller than women.<br>
                Your t-test shows an average height of 175.4 cm for men and an average height of 161.7 cm for women, with an estimate of the true difference ranging from 10.2cm to infinity. 
                The p-value is 0.002.<br>
                <b>Step 4:</b> <br>
                Assume in this case, the significant level is 0.05. <br>
                In your analysis of the difference in average height between men and women, you find that the p-value of 0.002 is below your cutoff of 0.05, 
                so you decide to reject your null hypothesis of no difference. <br>
                <b>Step 5:</b> <br>
                In our comparison of mean height between men and women we found an average difference of 14.3cm and a p-value of 0.002; therefore, we can refuse the null hypothesis that men are not taller than women and 
                conclude that there is likely a difference in height between men and women.
               </p>
