              <h2>4. Regression</h2>
              <p>Regression Analysis is a set of statistical analysis used for estimate the relationship between dependent vriable (y)
                and one or more independent variables (x). It can also be used for modelling and predicting future analysis. <br><br>
                There are three main types of regression analysis: <br>
                <ul class="box">
                  <li><b>Single Linear Regression</b> is statistical study used for estimate and study the relationship between two continous variables. 
                  One variable which is a dependent variable and another variable which is a indepdent variable. Formula can be written as: <br>
                  <b>y = b<sub>0</sub> + x<sub>1</sub>b<sub>1</sub> + error term </b> <br><br>
                  There are some assumption that need to make in order perform linear regression: <br><br>
                  <ul class="box">
                    <li>1. The dependent and independent variable show a linear relationship between the slope and the intercept </li>
                    <li>2. The independent variable is not random</li>
                    <li>3. The value of residual (error term) is zero</li>
                    <li>4. The value of residual (error term) is constant across all observations</li>
                    <li>5. The value of the residual (error term) is not correlated across all observations.</li>
                    <li>6. The residual (error term) values follow the normal distribution.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                  <li><b>Multiple Linear Regression</b> is similar to linear regression and similar assumption. However, it has multiple independent variables. 
                  and with one extra condition. <br><br>
                  <ul>
                    <li><b>Non_collinearity:</b> All independent variables should show a minimum correlation between each other. If the independent variables are highly correlated
                      with each other, it will be hard to access the true relationship between independent variable and dependent variable. 
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                  </li>
                  <li><b>Non-linear Regression</b>: Some of the variables relationship that we have are not always going to be linear relationship, that why we will need a 
                  non-linear relationship. This will add flexibility to the dataset and variables. However, how to fit the model and make prediction is out of the scope for this 
                  course. 
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
